author: @kenflip
processed_text: It's not correct that private equity firms value their portfolios arbitrarily. Any reasonable PE Fund these days has (1) an independent valuation firm look at valuations, because LPs insist on this; and (2) valuations are audited.Fees are also disclosed to investors, he should know this if he was a meaningful PE investor (eg ILPA template).The return numbers are also not right, as the endowments who have been PE/VC heavy have outperformed the S&P clearly for decades now.There is a lot of BS in PE marketing, and a lot of unearned hubris in PE. But there is a lot of that in silicon valley tech too. Confusing the tech bro swagger with underlying value that tech as a whole is creating is a mistake.  The median tech startup fails. Confusing median PE returns with PE as an asset class is the same error. He himself notes that strong market returns will attract a herd.Pension funds, sovereign wealth funds and endowments DO benchmark against index funds. Any sane financial board will do this....he is underestimating the basic intelligence of asset managers almost unconscionably.Anyway. There is some truth in what he says but he also has an axe to grind and there are basic flaws in his reasoning. Investors in PE are not retail. They are the largest and most sophisticated asset managers in the world. It's easy to point a finger at them and say they're dumb, but they really are not, and they are multi-asset so they know clearly the relative performance of asset classes. Managers who do not make returns lose their jobs. Period. This idiocy around managers being able to hang around with bad returns is professorial fantasy. In the real world, failure to produce actual, cash returns means losing your job. It's as simple as that. Endowments need to fund actual cash needs. Pension funds need to fund actual pensions. Managers who failed to outperform the market are fired quickly when returns don't materialist because the cash drawdown for these investors is real and mission-critical.

processed_text: If Mary did 'know' everything about seeing a color, then she would have that bodily experience of the process of seeing the color in her memory and be able to recall it. A process is organized into a unit by a reflective consciousness. The process of seeing a color requires an organizing principle reflecting on the process that is occurring and reorganizing the input into an recallable experience.  That is all included in the knowledge of what a color experience is.

processed_text: Dr. Lisa, in response to the audience member's inquiry regarding whether a machine equipped with AI can experience emotions while driving a car, I hold the perspective that despite its intricate electric circuitry, such a machine cannot replicate human emotions. This deficiency arises from its lack of the intricate complexity found in the abstract layers of the human brain, including consciousness, sentience, and a profound cognitive framework. Additionally, the scientific community has yet to establish a consensus on how to define and translate these attributes into tangible, physical terms. Without a clear understanding of these fundamental aspects of human experience, it remains challenging, if not impossible, to imbue machines with the same abilities as humans. Therefore, until we achieve a deeper understanding of these phenomena, machines will not possess the capacity for emotions and cognition that humans inherently possess. Any attempt to engineer such abilities into AI systems would require a fundamental grasp of these elusive concepts.We havent even agreed on what is "Conscioousness" per se! Forget agreeing on a carte blanche framework for the abstract layers! Despite these shortcomings, if technology leadership hastily invests millions and billions to develop AI systems erroneously incorporating some semblance of these elusive and mysterious human attributes, without grounding such developments in fundamental research agreements across the medical sciences, particularly in neuroscientific consensus, we are likely to encounter significant chaos in technological outcomes. I hope this post reaches Google Labs and hopefully,  helps them save tons of money!

author: @patriciabethbarker584
processed_text: I had tumors removed from my left parotid gland in my face 3 times (1982, 1984 and 1986) and radiation treatments in 1986.  9 lymph nodes were removed, as well as the gland and tumors.  About 10 years ago, I started noticing swelling on my left shoulder.  Fast forward to today....  I have lymphedema now.  Medical Drs only get 1 hour to 30 minutes of learning about Lymphedema in school.  Know that your Dr most likely knows less than you do about your symptoms and what can be done to assit your health.  Some will DENY you have a problem because they are uninformed.I have lymphedema on my head and neck area.  The radiation was on my left jaw and the lymph nodes that were removed came from my left neck and shoulder area.  I was told by one physician that I could not have lymphedema because it always happened in the leg area!   YIKES!  What a mistruth.  I have discovered you need to take charge of your own solutions if you have lymphedema or risk discomfort.It is essential you learn as much as possible about the lymphatic system.  Educate yourself.  Take that knowledge with you and participate in your own health success.  After watching Kathy on this channel a few years ago, I have been successful in finding my own solutions.  I had to teach my medical care team what I knew, and they are better physicians for my sharing.  Take selenium.  It will help with the swelling.  Practice intermittent fasting and the keto diet.  Practice lymphatic brushing and find a massage therapist who specializes in lymphatic massage.  Ask the masseuse to teach you how to massage yourself properly.  Wear compression garments if you can afford to purchase them.  Use tape if it is suggested, to help the flow of your fluids.  A masseuse can help you learn where to put the tape.Good luck and thank Kathy Bates for sharing her own journey!  I would be crying daily and suffering more if it weren't for finding this YouTube channel which led me to solutions.

processed_text: I have chronic cellulitis leg infections and accompanying edema for years now. Venous insufficiently (inferior cuspid valves) contribute as a cause. author: @QuicksilverSG
processed_text: @37:48 Becker: "Then [Bell] says... there's something else funny about Bohm's version of quantum physics. It has this spooky action at a distance. The position of a particle way over here can instantaneously affect the behavior of a pilot wave way over here."This is a mischaracterization of both Bohmian Mechanics and of Bell's commentary. As Becker explained earlier, in BM, pilot waves guide the movements of particles. However, there is no mechanism by which a particle's position can influence the behavior of its pilot wave, instantaneously or not. The pilot wave that guides the motion of the particle is not "over here" (i.e. separated by some physical distance). Pilot waves do not propagate across physical space-time, they manifest solely in Configuation Space, the complex-valued domain of potentially limitless numbers of dimensions where the quantum wave-function is defined.Becker then shifts gears into philosophical musings, and in doing so, short changes Bohm almost as much as did promoters of the Copenhagen Interpretation. What Becker glossed over was the main conclusion of Von Neumann's erroneous proof: the claim that quantum mechanics rules out ALL hidden variable theories, such as Bohmian Mechanics. What Bell discovered was that it is only LOCAL hidden variable theories that are ruled out, but NOT the non-local Pilot Wave theory of Bohm. Bell's Theorem actually vindicates Bohmian Mechanics, as did the recent Nobel Prize-winning experiments that confirmed Bell's predictions.Becker's historical account of quantum mechanics is nevertheless quite compelling. What happened next was even more provocative: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TvDCMS9bk74

author: @adrimiq
processed_text: 25:28 I have an issue with this whole "FT need to be rewritten and reworked so that they can pass *the right messages*" If that is the case, then we can't read Charles Perrault anymore. And even some stories by the Brothers Grimm. If the main richness of Fairy Tales is meant to be its direct consequences on reality, then they're locked in a moral code that will eventually become limited.Isn't the power of imagination so great, that it allows us to go to places that aren't the real world? How can we know what the real world is when we haven't experienced what it isn't? And, if ALL children (because I'm in doubt about them all being so naive) are really afraid of well-meaning stepmothers, is it really the fairy tale that needs to be changed, instead of the education of children in regards to identifying the difference between fiction and reality? Or, in a deeper sense, shouldn't we all be questioning our relationship towards art and storytelling, if we are so keen to reduce it to a simple "manual on how to live our lives"?

author: @bluetech2809
processed_text: On the point of buying vs renting a home, one consideration should be whether buying a home (with a mortgage with no deposit) will result in a significantly lower monthly payment. If you're paying $1000/month for rent but you could buy a home and have a monthly mortgage payment of $500, that might end up being a better option. Of course there are risks, like if you want/need to move for different/better job opportunities, you have to decide what you're going to do with that home (versus being able to move more freely when renting). There's also the fact that if you were (hypothetically) saving $500/month, that's an extra $500 that can go toward investments or savings.

Innovation on the other hand is protected by IP because of sometimes economic reasons and at all times because of political reasons. Now our ancestors would protect this by just passing down their innovations to their direct offspring. Now, what actually gave an edge to the Westerners' provisioned Science is the liberalization of markets, which created more competition and thus valued innovations as a source of market capitalization and therefore added value to the science that issued the said innovations. author: @joshdunne8792
processed_text: In 2014 i injured my back and from being the healthiest I'd ever been at 14 years old i suddenly became the worst I'd ever been. My right leg was amputated before i turned 1 and I'd resolved all other medical issues to point where i just had to worry about looking after my prosthetic leg.This one injury (where i suffered muscle damage to my left leg and my lower back) caused chronic pain in my spine even after the muscle damage healed. It has triggered chronic pain in my joints: shoulders, elbows, hands, knuckles, hips, knees and my ankle and toes. For the first year or two after my injury i didn't sleep. And I'm not exaggerating i would go to bed at 10 pm and lay awake until my alarm went off for school at 7 am. I ended up setting my alarm for 8 and because I'd actually fall asleep around 6 am, 7 am.I spent that time (about 2 years, 2014 to 2016) trying to function and manage school by getting maximum 3 hours of sleep over 3 days and then crashing and sleeping for 12 hours to 20 hours per night over the next 2 or 3 days.I had to start taking opioids (strong pain killers) at 15 to sleep. The orthopaedics doctor did not want to do this. But i could not function. I was in agony, sleep deprived and failing secondary school (13 to 17 years old). First year was fine not great i was never a straight A student. But my grades plummeted in second year after this illness/chronic pain started.Now I'm 23 and have a pretty good routine where i sleep 12 midnight to 12 mid day. Matthews talks and interviews have helped me manage a lot better over the recent past few years. But from like 14 years old (2014) to 16 years old (2016) i had lots of trial and error.Now even with my condition managed (it's not a good life so i use managed very regretfully) If i sleep 9 hours or less i want to f@ck!ng d!e... i sleep for 12 hours a night if i can.Matt has spoken once in a little detail about illness and sleep in a recent interview on Hubermans podcast. I wish he'd speak more about sleep and illness

author: @100ActsofLove
processed_text: I know this is an old video, but it made me soooooo mad!  My husband died at the age of 44 of cancer in 2009. We were given the option of hospice four days before he died. He was already unconscious by then.  I was told by the doctor four days before he died, "You can do hospice, but it will take a while to set up. He may not live long enough." We should have been given the option of hospice. It would have made the last three weeks of his life so much more enjoyable and at peace and mine filled with so much less anxiety and our kids...it would have been huge for them.  I do feel lucky that I was able to be there with him in the hospital when he died, but he would have loved to see his coworkers, his students, and his team one last time. While watching this video, what took me by surprise was how sad (and angry) I feel, almost 15 years later, that we weren't given that chance because they tried to keep him alive when really it was over weeks before. I just feel heartbroken at the moment.  Everyone who loved him deserved better.

author: @JonRoy_ZA
processed_text: @@FerdarPleaseSubscribe There are several criticisms of Marxism, some of which include: 1. Economic inefficiency: Critics argue that Marxism's emphasis on centralized economic planning and state ownership of the means of production can lead to inefficiency and lack of innovation. 2. Lack of incentives: Some critics argue that Marxism's focus on collective ownership and distribution of resources can lead to a lack of individual incentives for innovation and hard work. 3. Suppression of individual freedom: Critics contend that Marxism's focus on the collective can lead to the suppression of individual freedoms and rights. 4. Historical failures: Critics point to historical examples of Marxist regimes that have been associated with authoritarianism, human rights abuses, and economic stagnation. 5. Overemphasis on class struggle: Some critics argue that Marxism's emphasis on class struggle oversimplifies complex social dynamics and ignores other important factors such as culture, identity, and individual agency. 6. Lack of political pluralism: Critics argue that Marxist societies tend to be characterized by a lack of political pluralism and the suppression of dissenting voices.Finally, the man hated God. processed_text: Sharon Salzberg quote highlights from this video: ‚Äú(Lovingkindness) is meant to be a live, vital sense of connection‚Äîto not feel so isolated, not to isolate others, to have a sense of being a part of a greater whole.‚Äù‚ÄúWhat's it like when we're not considering ourselves separate and apart? Where the kind of constructs of ‚Äòself‚Äô and ‚Äòother‚Äô and ‚Äòus‚Äô and ‚Äòthem‚Äô‚Äîthe great big ‚Äòother‚Äô out there‚Äîare seen as constructs?‚Äù‚ÄúThe reality is that we live in an interconnected universe. It's a world that's pointing to that all of the time. But our values, our behavior, don't always reflect that truth.‚Äù‚ÄúBeing able to see more clearly, to see more accurately, to see the interconnected nature of things, is one of the strongest ways to leap into a sense of lovingkindness.‚Äù‚ÄúLove doesn't mean you like everybody. It actually doesn't even mean you necessarily like anybody. But we do understand our lives have something to do with one another. It's a deep, deep acknowledgement that we do live in this kind of world of connection.‚Äù‚ÄúInterconnection is that fundamental recognition that what happens over there doesn't nicely stay over there. It really ripples out over here. And what we do, where we put our energy, what we care about, it matters because it's going to ripple out in just that same way.‚Äù‚ÄúMeditation is a practice of resilience.‚Äù‚ÄúOur assumptions of aloneness and a sense of isolation, our assumptions of fundamental difference, are really assumptions. And we get to question them.‚Äù‚ÄúThe fundamental question is, what do we think love is? And does it bring us down? Does it make us stupid? Does it make us sentimental? Or, can it be this kind of clarifying vision of the way the world actually is and how we can respond to it?‚Äù‚ÄúRemember that our goal is to just let go and begin again. If you have to do that billions of times, that doesn't mean you're doing it wrong. You're doing fine ‚Ä¶ No matter how many times you may have to let go and begin again, it's not a problem. That's the point, actually.‚Äù‚ÄúThe most important moment is the moment after you've been distracted, after you've been lost.‚Äù‚ÄúToday, with unprecedented threats to our planet and divisions among people, awareness of our interdependence is no longer optional. It's critical that we widen our attention to include those we encounter as we go about our daily lives.‚Äù‚ÄúAs our experiences of the universality of suffering grows, our sense of interconnection deepens, and we begin to wish others could be free in a new way, in spite of their actions, their beliefs, or their positions in the world.‚Äù‚ÄúOne of the great hindrances people face is their expectations.‚Äù‚ÄúEquanimity doesn't mean indifference, coldness, or withdrawal. author: @tanbir2358
processed_text: Unlocking Business Value Through Compelling StoriesIntroduction:Aswath Damodaran, the renowned authority on investment valuation, shares invaluable insights into the power of storytelling in business and its impact on company valuations. The Soul in ValuationDamodaran emphasizes that valuation is not just about numbers on a spreadsheet. The story behind the valuation adds meaning and purpose, giving soul to the process. By sharing anecdotes and real-world examples, Damodaran compellingly demonstrates how having faith in your valuations is crucial for taking actionable steps in business. The Delusions of Number Crunchers and StorytellersDelving into the delusions of number crunchers and storytellers, Damodaran humorously unveils the pitfalls each group faces. From the precision and objectivity delusions of number crunchers to the creativity and reliance on anecdotal evidence delusions of storytellers, he exposes the humorous yet critical errors of both mindsets. Crafting a Compelling Story for ValuationUnderstanding a business and evaluating its value is imperative, acknowledges Damodaran. He stresses the importance of converting the story into numbers for valuation and seeking feedback from diverse perspectives to enhance the narrative. Real-world examples of companies like Uber and Ferrari vividly illustrate his insights. Questioning and Analyzing Business StoriesDamodaran emphasizes the importance of asking if a business story is possible, plausible, and probable. By scrutinizing scenarios of implausible and improbable stories, he demonstrates the critical nature of questioning and pushing back on assumptions in valuation. Real-world cases like Uber and Theranos are dissected to exemplify his points. The Impact of Describing a Company on Its Perceived ValueSharing thought-provoking insights, Damodaran explores how describing a company can significantly influence its perceived value. Real-world examples such as Uber and the online advertising industry are used to illuminate the persuasive role of storytelling in shaping the narrative and impacting valuation. Embracing Humility and Faith in ValuationAddressing the psychological and faith-based aspects of valuation, Damodaran delves into the necessity of having faith in valuation, likening it to a belief system. Compellingly, he explains how embracing humility, admitting mistakes, and taking ownership of investments are vital components in the journey of investment valuation. Tech Companies and the Redefinition of Capital ExpendituresIn a forward-thinking segment, Damodaran advocates for redefining and expanding the concept of capital expenditures, shedding light on the insufficiency of traditional definitions to capture investment in growth. Real-world examples from tech giants like Google and Intel enrich his argument, emphasizing the importance of adapting to evolving industries. Conclusion:Aswath Damodaran's thought-provoking insights underscore the transformative impact of storytelling in business valuation. By bridging the gap between numbers and narrative, business leaders can unlock untapped value and navigate critical decision-making with resilience and clarity.

author: @coffeecat086
processed_text: We need  so many more people like him. I started school right after the ADA was enforced. My teachers and school mates were relentless in bullying me. I am legally blind in my left eye (20/500 ) and totally blind in the right. I am autistic, have epilepsy and hard of hearing, though this didn‚Äôt become apparent until high school. The teacher from K-6th grade knew this was going on and quite a few of them perpetuated it. The principal allowed the funds that were set aside for my equipment and services to be used on the construction of a workout room for the staff. She even had the nerve to tell me I should go to the school for the blind which was 400 miles from our family home. She said it would ‚Äúbe easier on the teachers‚Äù. I was pushed down flights of stairs regularly, had my finished homework stolen and copied from with the implication that I had cheated. My belongings were taken from me and students openly mocked me. All of this was allowed to occur with no consequence to those involved. I was regularly sat at something called a zero table when I stood up for myself and refused to do my schoolwork until it was formatted for my needs. I even left the school, as instructed by my mother?we lived a block from the school ) j it took over an hour and a half for the principal to come to the door and ask about my wellbeing. I went to the school for the blind to get relief from the situation in 7th and &8th grade. Luckily in high school, which I attended at home was far far less traumatic. I had become proficient in braille by then. My son is autistic also and I am so thankful that he is an to have a better experience than I did.

processed_text: - Fun stuff. It's refreshing to hear this instrument kept alive in new works. Properly reproduced, it has a breadth of voice that escapes the trite envelope of simply mean tone in recordings; to wit- if we wanted only the pitch itself, instead of a harpsichord with its attendant clicks and clunks, we'd settle for MIDI, yes? Bandoneon has a very full complement of treats.- As Piazzolla expressed, not all tango music (to generalize the dance sound) need be danced (hear his Estaciones Porte√±as, for an example of rich chamber style). To incorporate a modern twist to this form in dance is quite groovy- more of that keeping alive idea. The music itself in this one works either way to me- but as a chamber work it's superb, again to me, subjectively. Thank all these folks for their passion for this great form(!)(and as a side note- why is it entirely in character that Gobble would present something as classy as shoes on the furniture? author: @kidlitfanful
processed_text: I had to drop, among other things, dairy, pork and beef from my diet around my GERD diagnosis, and Penn is so right about not craving stuff you used to think was good/you couldn't live without.He's told a story about how someone asked what, as an atheist, kept from from r@ping and (unaliving) and he replied that he does those things to as many people as he wants, and that number is ZERO! Though I started eating fewer animals for my own health, chicken doesn't bother me, but got out of the habit wanting an animal to die for my tastebuds, even when going Rare and Appropriate.  I went to a nice restaurant around the new year and a few of us ordered baked potatoes on the side, and the server brought various ramekins of garnish we could add.  I never would have wanted the green onions, at one time I would have drowned that potato in sour cream, but it didn't sound good, and the little bowl of bacon bits might as well have been a carcass for all found it appetizing, when just a year before I would have been all "Mmm, baconnnn!" a la Homer Simpson.It's nice to be able to walk miles without getting winded (the acid of GERD doesn't just hurt your stomach, it affects lung function, and for a while, I had to rest after only half a block!), but it's neat to literally crave stuff that's good for me, like broccoli, and to find carrots sweet like candy!  And I crave sweet potatoes with a little sweet chili sauce like Penn craves his blueberry cayenne bowl!

author: @HadesMortis
processed_text: When I thought about this, I had some example in mind that, at least in my moral compass (to some extent), answered what approach should I take considering that we live in CAPITALISM. Imagine situation, with two workers. Worker A:Income: 1 unit of wealth per time period.Charity: Follows Singer's approach, donating 0.8 units of wealth to charity, leaving 0.2 units for basic needs.Outcome: Over time, Worker A struggles with demotivation and burnout due to the lack of sufficient personal investment. This impacts their productivity and overall well-being, potentially reducing their future earnings and ability to contribute to charity. After several years, Worker A continues to earn 1 unit of wealth per period, donating a total of 0.8 units each period.Worker B:Income: 1 unit of wealth per time period.Charity: Initially donating 0.1 units of wealth to charity, investing 0.9 units in personal well-being and productivity.Outcome: Worker B uses the additional resources for health, education, and activities that enhance motivation and productivity. Over time, this investment leads to increased earnings. For example, after several years, Worker B's income grows to 10 units of wealth per period due to improved skills and higher productivity. Now, Worker B donates 1 unit of wealth to charity (10% of their income), which is higher than Worker A's donations both in absolute and relative terms.Moral Accountability for Worker B:An important aspect is the commitment that Worker B makes as a moral actor at the beginning of their working journey. Worker B promises to donate a small portion of their income (0.1 units) to charity initially, while investing the rest in improving their own quality of life. This investment should be directed towards activities that boost their productivity and future earning potential. Worker B's lifestyle, which may include luxuries that enhance their well-being and productivity, is justified as long as their wealth and ability to contribute to charity grow over time.However, if Worker B's wealth does not increase significantly over a prolonged period, despite the investments in personal well-being, they are morally obligated to reassess their spending. In such a case, Worker B should reduce their spending on luxuries and increase their charitable contributions. This ensures that the goal of maximizing overall charitable impact is met.By the end of the period, Worker B has contributed more to charity overall (1 unit out of 10) compared to Worker A (0.8 units out of 1), while maintaining a higher quality of life and greater economic stability.

author: @triplea657aaa
processed_text: I think that while this argument held quite well in the time of its writing, it is no longer true that the causes such as starvation are the result of a lack of potential resources. These issues are now almost entirely issues of politics and logistics, which makes the need to sacrifice luxuries to ameliorate these things quite small as throwing a bit more money at disease research really doesn't do very much good while investing in one's local community can have a great deal of impact to those involved. There is also the problem of gradation. The marginal good of donating some amount of money versus the marginal bad of losing one's luxuries depends greatly on so many factors that one cannot even approximate anything of use. What perchance is a luxury? Is eating higher quality food a luxury? Is eating more than a minimal caloric input a luxury? Both of which would cause minor and great negative impacts on the person who is giving them up and may in fact reduce the value of what they are capable of contributing on a day to day basis. If I starve myself for lack of want of waste, my performance will decline and the net benefit to society of my daily work will be reduced. If I eat cheaper but less healthy food, a reduced but similar effect will occur. If I do not grant myself any entertainment, I shall get bored and possibly depressed and my productivity shall falter from this as well. The sheer complexity of such calculations make the practical utility of this argument utterly absurd. We can assuredly find waste in our lives that could be better used for the pursuit of the good and most people are horrendously wasteful in such regards, but as an argument on how to formulate the actions of people, this argument simply cannot do anything but fail.

author: @alexisborden3191
processed_text: To the Indian guy asking about command.  Yes command is important, but less so than movement, at least at the major league level, they can all generally hit their spots.  But the graph isn't looking at that, its just looking at movement of a pitch.  Because, and this part is key, all else being equal, pitches with more movement are hard to hit.  Sliders that break more, sinkers that break more, and fastballs that stay up longer.  I suppose fastballs are the exception in that spinning them faster makes them move less.  But the point is that batters expect fastballs to drop a certain amount.  If the ball doesn't drop as much as they've seen throughout their careers, then the batter is gonna swing under the fastball.  And generally, movement is going to be more conducive to success than command will be, because even pitchers with great command miss, but movement is fairly consistent, and a fastball with good velocity and spin is going to harder to hit than its lower spin lower velo counterpart, even if its in a bad spot.

author: @alexisborden3191
processed_text: There are also defensive metrics.  DRS and UZR, and not available during this talk but its available now is statcast OAA.  To a degree I think he's just talking about offense because its easier to measure than pitching or defense.  I don't think he's saying offense is the most important part.  That said, defense is only so valuable.  A team with average defense and the top 10 hitters in the league will do better than a team of average hitters who happen to be the top 10 defenders in the league.  The reason is much of defense is purely down to pitching, there's nothing position players can do about 2 walks and a home run, there's no way for the fielders to prevent or even mitigate that.  Its a question of balances, you can't just punt pitching entirely, you'll allow more runs than you could ever score if you just ignore pitching.  But there are many ways to build a ball club.  IMO whether you're going to "stack offense" or "stack defense" isn't really a question that needs to be asked.  I think most teams are just going to get the best available players they can, take the Astros for example, Kyle Tucker is well rounded, he's a great hitter good defender, provides good value in all areas.  Chas McCormick is only an ok hitter but plays good defense.  Yordan Alvarez isn't very good defensively, but he's one of, if not The best hitter in baseball.  I think a lot of today's analysis is down to how much defense is equivalent to how much offense or how much baserunning.  Do you want say Matt Chapman or Jose Ramirez, what's gonna get more value, Chapman's defense, or Ramirez's offence, or maybe they're pretty close to the same value at the end of the day.  I say those 2 as examples I don't actually have an opinion on which one is better.

author: @alexisborden3191
processed_text: I mean, this isn't really the case anymore, while yes the current definition was established in 1996 umpires still erroneously called strikes too far on the outside of the plate.  The thing that reigned that in was pitch tracking data, umpires would look at games afterward as seen which pitches were actually balls and strikes and adjusted accordingly.  For the most part, any ball strike errors aren't in specific places, they're just the umpire getting fooled by catcher framing.  The only case of "having a different zone" is especially tall or short batters, like Aaron Judge, or Jose Altuve, because umpires are used to most players knees being a certain height, and what looks like a strike at the bottom of the zone, is actually just below the bottom of Aaron Judge's knees.

processed_text: Although I was a little confused with this slide as well, and I think it could've been designed better, here's how I ended up interpreting the numbers:1. skilled negotiators showed 2.3 irritators per hours (e.g., self-praise, implied unfairness) vs. average negotiators at 10.8, implying that skilled negotiators were fairer than average negotiators, as average negotiators were about 5x (10.8 / 2.3 = 4.7) more likely to be unfair in relative terms2. skilled negotiators offered 5.1 options for negotiation per issue vs. average negotiators at 2.6, meaning skilled negotiators offered 2x more options to consider than average negotiatorsThe rest I believe could've also been in the actual count of events vs. percentages, but I wonder if he decided to go with percentages because the counts were much higher in tens or hundreds of events, which could potentially make it easier to add unwanted bias between line items. If it were up to me, I might've either separated them in 2 tables with consistent units per table, use a consistent unit across all line items, or use an index which is neither a percentage nor a count.

processed_text: This lecture was a very pivotal part of my change in diet. In my mid 20s I had this notion that I was indestructible and that I could eat anything I wanted. I have more clarity of thought, improved sleep, and I have not been sick in at least 2 years, no COVID or even a cold. I am not saying my experience will necessarily be the same as other people‚Äôs, and I‚Äôm not saying a vegan diet will solve all your problems, but it‚Äôs a step in the right direction and it seems most nutritional research supports that.

processed_text: problem with the Chinese room situation has to do with the representations would never be dense enough in the room. In principle the ''room' can understand' is correct but it's not likely, as the representation matters (and such simple & linear mappings affect the representation & context) hence it also can be true that ''room' does not  understand', which is usually the case.  Hence it's the representations and their manipulation that matters. So what, well the then next question is does the machine doing to the computations have the dense abstraction representation of 'self' and 'experience' and 'understanding of a given concept'. This is why the human is usually the only 'person' or 'aware agent' in the room. In a way it's only the updating of the representations and the representations that 'understand' -- kinda odd to say the room understands, pending what you mean and what is doing the manipulations, might be better to say it's the system that understands pending the context provided to itself.If you want sentient ai simply look at how our reward model steered our representations to give some animals some varying levels of agency and autonomy and observers. author: @foodchewer
processed_text: @@LoraxChannel You're absolutely right, and the threat of slipping further into what Yannis Varoufakis calls "technofeudalism" is even greater. Technological or scientific process is NOT synonymous with social or institutional progress. At all. I see this is a mistake people make all the time: they see that we have great medical care, state of the art developments in predicting, diagnosing, and treating diseases, high definition television, incredible communications technology, self driving cars, etc. and assume we're in some golden age. No, far from it. As a friend I spoke to recently said, "technological progress is value-neutral". Now, I'm not trying to be a Luddite here necessarily, but just pointing out that in order for technological and scientific gains to really mean something, there have to be corresponding social, economic, and institutional gains made. These last three seem to have been largely forgotten though and our world appears to get increasingly unequal in terms of wealth and influence. We are creating the conditions for profound inequalities and have no cause to be talking about progress.

processed_text: I really love this movie! Sir Ian, Laura, and Milo were superb! The English do it better than we Americans, I believe, because, they take such care to deliver beautiful sets and cinematography. To Mr. Ian McKellan: I do go to the library (going today as a matter of fact), and the greatest pleasures I get from library days are the heavenly scent of all the books when you walk in, as well as being around other people who love books. I still remember the day I was able to get an adult card. I was so proud to finally be able to check out any book in the library, instead of being confined to the children's section. Not everybody loves books these days. It's getting rarer, I fear. Anyway, I spend hours there and get as many books that my book bag will hold, and I bring them home. I really hate to leave the library. I keep the books through both renews, until I'm forced to bring them back, and then I do it all over again. I take full advantage of inter-library loans and holds. Library days have and will always be such VERY special days of my life.

processed_text: üìö Barbara Oakley discusses effective learning techniques and the importance of observation in a story.00:00 Barbara Oakley emphasizes the significance of effective learning methods. Observation and people watching play a role in the story shared by Barbara Oakley.  üß† Exploring new learning methods inspired by military engineers to improve problem-solving skills.06:14 Military engineers' problem-solving skills were exceptional and inspired a new approach to learning. Seeking to change brain functions to learn like top professors worldwide in various challenging subjects.  üß† Importance of shifting thinking modes to solve problems effectively.12:35 Shifting to a different mode of thinking when stuck on a problem is crucial for effective problem-solving. Taking a break and engaging in activities that shift focus away from the problem can lead to better problem-solving approaches. Example of Salvador Dali showcasing the importance of shifting thinking modes for creativity and problem-solving.  ‚è≥ Effective technique to combat procrastination: Pomodoro Technique for focused work sessions.19:21 Use the Pomodoro Technique by setting a timer for focused work sessions Eliminate distractions during the work session for maximum concentration Regularly assess your focus during the session to maintain productivity  üß† Exercise is crucial for learning as new neurons are constantly being born, essential for memory.25:52 Exercise plays a vital role in the learning process by promoting the birth of new neurons Contrary to previous belief, individuals are not born with a set number of neurons for life New neurons in the hippocampus are essential for learning and remembering new information  üß† Effective learning involves spaced repetition to prevent metabolic vampires from erasing new patterns.32:46 Spaced repetition helps embed patterns in long-term memory Cramming leads to loss of learning due to metabolic vampires Analogize learning process to building a wall for better understanding  üí° Benefits of poor working memory in enhancing creativity and idea generation.38:30 Poor working memory can lead to increased creativity by allowing new ideas to slip in. Individuals with weak working memory may struggle to hold ideas but tend to be more creative. Research indicates that Attention Deficit Disorder can also contribute to enhanced creativity.  üìö Importance of testing, flashcards, and memorization in learning various subjects.44:55 Testing is more effective than studying alone, use flashcards for learning, and memorization enhances understanding in math and science. Flashcards are beneficial for all subjects, not just languages, and can deepen the connection to the material being learned. Homework should not be treated as a one-time task, but rather as an opportunity to enhance understanding through repetition and memorization.  üß† Utilize chunking to break down complex problems and switch between focused and diffuse modes for effective learning.51:51 Chunking involves breaking down information into manageable parts to enhance understanding and memory Switching between focused mode for concentrated learning and diffuse mode for making random connections aids in problem-solving Engaging in activities like sleeping, walking, or showering can help in making creative connections during diffuse mode  üß† Importance of mastering one technique in learning mathematics to avoid confusion and promote understanding.57:05 Kumon Mathematics is recommended for its focus on practice, repetition, and building mastery in math concepts. Mastering one technique in mathematics is crucial for building a strong foundation and avoiding confusion. Learning multiple techniques simultaneously can be overwhelming and hinder progress in understanding mathematics.  üìò Effective learning strategies: Interleaving, repetition, and flexibility.1:03:06 Interleaving different problem types in learning enhances flexibility. Repetition of problems should be mixed with interleaving for better learning outcomes. Application of learned techniques in various contexts improves understanding and skill retention.

author: @slowwco
processed_text: Diane Musho Hamilton quote highlights from this video: ‚Äú‚ÄòMeditate‚Äô and ‚Äòmediate‚Äô both literally mean ‚Äòto bring two into one.‚Äô With meditation, when you sit down on the cushion, you're bringing your body, speech, and mind into one moment and creating coherence with your life. So, you could say meditation is a way of becoming one with your life. Whereas mediation is about bringing two differing points of view, or two different sets of interests or a conflict in which there are many parties, into one solution.‚Äù‚ÄúConflict is, by its nature, threatening to the status quo.‚Äù‚ÄúCommit to experiencing the sensation. Stop the thoughts. Experience the sensation. Literally receive them. Get to know them.‚Äù‚ÄúMeditation is one of the great ways that we have of navigating our interior and heightening the discipline, if you will, of how we perceive.‚Äù‚ÄúWe all know that there are certain developmental tasks that get accomplished at certain ages (in children). But, the same is true of adults. We also can expand and grow our perspectives.‚Äù‚ÄúI started to see that there were limits to capacity. And the capacity that I started to notice was the capacity to take perspectives ‚Ä¶ What I was seeing was just a whole range of people who had different capacity to take different points of view.‚Äù‚ÄúIf you have two coexisting truths in your head at any one time, you literally have to deal with the disruption in your body.‚Äù‚ÄúThere was a much smaller group of people who not only could they hold one, two, perhaps three, they could hold four, five, six perspectives at once. They could take a perspective on the process. They could think about how the process had evolved from the past and where it might go in the future. They could think about what the impact of the facilitator was on the process.‚Äù‚ÄúThis perspective taking, and the capacity to take perspectives, changes the heart of negotiation at such a fundamental level.‚Äù‚ÄúI don't just assume that everybody's capacity is the same. I assume that there are differences in capacity and that I have to take that into account.‚Äù‚ÄúIn order to maintain an identity, there are things that I have to keep out of it. Jung referred to the shadow as anything that I cannot bring into my identity as me.‚Äù‚ÄúWhen human beings go to war with each other, one of the first things we do is dehumanize the enemy. Because the enemy has to become ‚Äònot me‚Äô. If it's not me, then I can abuse you, I can kill you, I can destroy you. But, as soon as you're like me, I no longer can do that.‚ÄùEgocentric self: ‚ÄúThe ego is not bad, the ego is limited. The ego is oriented toward self-sustaining. But, there is such a thing as a healthy ego. There's a healthy ecosystem of self which is permeable and which can take inputs and give out inputs. And, then the perspective can shift to include more. An ego becomes bad when an ego is exclusive. A healthy ego is one that has permeability and is able to drop its reference points and expand awareness ‚Ä¶ Wherever there's an egocentric self, there's a sense of the other, so there's self and other ‚Ä¶ One of the conditions that we want to pay attention to whenever we're identifying as the ego is that there's a sense of separation‚Äîand because there's a sense of separation, there's stress.‚ÄùEthnocentric self: ‚ÄúWe're going to grow our perspectives from the self to the group ‚Ä¶ The ethnocentric self feels safe in my group, but your group can sometimes feel threatening to me ‚Ä¶ The values were the ones of the people, my tribe, the people I belonged with ‚Ä¶ At the egocentric level, there's self and other; at the ethnocentric level, there‚Äôs us and them ‚Ä¶ The boundary around what's ‚Äòme‚Äô and what's ‚Äònot me‚Äô at ethnocentric is strong.‚ÄùWorld-centric self: ‚ÄúIf you can cross the barrier of ‚Äòus and them‚Äô, you're already established at what we would call a world-centric level of development ‚Ä¶ In the same way the ego is too small, then all of a sudden, so is my ethnocentric identity ‚Ä¶ At ethnocentric, difference is threatening. At world-centric, difference is embraced ‚Ä¶ My capacity to identify with all of humanity and to really enjoy and appreciate the differences is fully online.‚ÄùCosmic-centric self: ‚ÄúCosmic-centric transcends and includes world-centric, healthy ethnocentrism, and healthy egocentric ‚Ä¶ Where is that boundary of identity? You're limitless ‚Ä¶ I can't quite identify the boundaries of space or time ‚Ä¶ Identity itself has dissolved, and when identity itself dissolves, I'm completely open. And, I'm relaxed in a way that's really fundamental. I feel really at home ‚Ä¶ I'm completely in the here and now, my awareness is wide open, there's no sense of limit ‚Ä¶ There's nothing that is beyond what I am, so I'm simply embedded in the breadth of all things.‚Äù

author: @JessieThorne886
processed_text: I'm a psychologist, so selling my work is harder, because bosses don't see me doing therapy, but I hope they at least hear from my patients that they're happy. The autism helps me see complex patterns in people's problems and pick up on every little micro-expression, etc, plus I'm allowed to put what discrepancies I see into words, and there are scripts on how to treat every kind of problem. Of course, the person would probably get a different treatment from a neurotypical therapist, but most of my clients tell me they feel the treatment is very helpful. They say I'm annoyingly direct, but that that's what helped them, since I told it to them straight, where they can hide with other therapists. I have this childish urge to self-reveal at the end of a therapy and declare "and btw, you were helped by a person with autism" üòÇ

author: @JessieThorne886
processed_text: It's so nice to hear from her that you can be autistic and be adept at visual thinking. author: @Howtobe777
processed_text: I love dennett. Everything made sense. Except for the free will stuff. He's clearly afraid something horrible would happen to society and the law if people came to understand that free will doesn't really exist. I don't share his fear. Most people denying free will seem very sensible grounded individuals. And the reasons they give are much better than the strawman Dennett presents here. I think his fear took him over and much intelligent people have many ways of rationalising their fears to themselves. His compatibilism never really took off outside of academia, and that's probably for the better. Not in the least for all his own other work. It's all genetics and memetics, and the self is a benign user illusion... but it has free will? It is not needed to make this move. But it is very hard to change your mind on something you've written and published a book about. I think his slight of hand on the free will thing will be soon forgotten and all his amazing work on consciousness, the self, religion, evolution and memetics will live on for a long long time. Thank you dennett for being an inspiration for generations to come. You've been thinking.

Whereas Reacher is down to earth and the consummate pragmatist, he‚Äôs also a true romantic. What we know about Cruise is opposite to both these things. He really does seem to be a cookey narcissist, with outrageous beliefs, who is is incapable of real empathy or emotional commitment. And however well Cruise acts, these days we just know far too much about him and it‚Äôs began to make it hard to like him as a person and this erodes our capacity for buying into any role he portrays that is at all sympathetic these days. Tom Cruise plays Tom Cruise. And if you don‚Äôt really like Tom Cruise, you don‚Äôt really want to se him portray a character you love.

processed_text: @@DonKelleyMusicActually, Aubrey pitched April to them and helped create the character. She spoke about this in an interview. When the show was casting, Aubrey was suggested by a casting director who was intrigued by her funny, unconventional energy and suggested she audition for the show. At the time, Aubrey wasn't looking to be in a sitcom but she went because she was already in LA for a movie she was doing, and as a then fan of The Office she was distracted by meeting at the same place that show was filming. Originally the character was going to be a dumb woman who messed up constantly and wouldn't last long, but when she met the showrunners, Aubrey told them that a better direction was the April you experience in the show. She pitched them the character's position, personality and role in the story, and she based much of April's nature on her sister. Even April's relationship with Andy was Aubrey's idea.

author: @lefthooklansing
processed_text: @@olgafatica3445 the point is that this was the world John Law lived in - one of silver money and barter. I'm not so interested in what happened 5000 years ago, but I am interested in what happened over the last 500 years, as society grew up."Before the use of Money was known, Goods were exchang'd by Barter, orContract; and Contracts were made payable in Goods. This State of Barter was inconvenient, and disadvantageous. 1. He who desir'd toBarter would not always find People who wanted the Goods he had, and had suchGoods as he desir'd in Exchange.2. Contracts taken payable in Goods were uncertain, for Goods of the same kinddiffer'd in value.3. There was no measure by which he Proportion of Value Goods had to oneanother could be known.In this State of Barter there was little Trade, and few Arts-men. The Peopledepended on the Landed-men. The Landed-men labour'd only so much of the Landas serv'd the occasions of their Families, to barter for such necessaries as theirLand did not produce; and to lay up for Seed and bad Years. What remain'd wasunlabour'd; or gifted on condition of Vassalage, and other Services.The Losses and Difficulties that attended Barter, would force the Landed-men to agreater consumption of the Goods of their own Product, and a lesser Consumptionof other Goods; or to supply themselves, they would turn the Land to the productof the several Goods they had occasion for; tho only proper to produce of onekind. So, much of the Land uas unlabour'd,what was labour'd was not employ'd tothat by which it would have turn'd to most Advantage, nor the People to theLabour they were most fit for.Silver as a Metal had a value in Barter, as other Goods; from the Uses it was thenapply'd to.As Goods of the same kind differ'd in value, so Silver differ'd from Silver, as itwas more or less fine.Silver was lyable to a change in its Value, as other Goods, from any change in itsQuantity, or in the Demand for it.Silver had Qualities which fitted it for the use of Money.1. It could be brought to a Standard in Fineness, so was certain as to its Quality.2. It was easie of Delivery.3. It was of the same value in one Place that it was in another; or differ'd little,being easie of carriage.4. It could be kept without Loss or Expense; taking up little Room, and beingdurable.5. It could be divided without Loss, an Ounce in four Pieces, being equal in Valueto an Ounce in one Piece.Silver having these Qualities, 'its reasonable to think it was used as Money, beforeit was coin'd... etc

processed_text: The great Kahneman said those 50% MIT/Harvard didn't bother to check their intuition. If they had, I guess many of them would come to the correct answer. Let's say they guess 0.10 (10 cents). Visually they see 1.10 + 0.10 = 1.20 => then their system 1 immediately "see" 1.05 + 0.05 = 1.10. This is delayed system 1. AI and expert systems  solve this problem differently. An expert system can do math like this: (x + 1) + x = 1.10 => x = 0.05. AI, as far as copilot is concerned, deduce the answer this way also.

author: @wolpumba4099
processed_text: AbstractCancer diagnosis and treatment heavily rely on microscopic analysis of pathology slides to determine tumor characteristics and the complex tumor microenvironment. This analysis is crucial for the success of cutting-edge treatments such as immunotherapy. However, the immense size and detail of pathology images pose significant challenges for typical vision transformers. The GigaPath project aims to tackle this by developing scalable architectures for modeling pathology images and creating a large-scale, multimodal, longitudinal foundation model.This project uses techniques like dilated attention (LongNet) to increase transformer scalability for such high-resolution images.  In collaboration with Providence Hospital, a massive real-world cancer patient dataset is being compiled, including clinical notes, genomics data, radiology images and reports, and pathology slides.  GigaPath explores self-supervised learning approaches across different modalities to make the most of this valuable data. The ultimate goal is to develop a foundation model that unlocks insights from this real-world data, advancing AI for cancer care and research. i used gemini

author: @wolpumba4099
processed_text: SummaryIntroduction to LASER Method  - 00:17 Introduction of the new method called LASER (Layer-Selective Rank Reduction) for improving pre-trained large language models (LLMs).  - 00:26 Discussion on the impact of LLMs on machine learning and their lack of complete understanding.  - 00:34 Explanation that LLMs are trained on diverse internet-collected data using transformer architectures.  - 00:49 Suggestion that understanding LLMs could be aided by intervening in the model and observing performance changes.   Explaining the LASER Intervention  - 01:15 Presentation of LASER, which involves selecting a weight matrix of an LLM and creating a low-rank approximation of it.  - 01:32 Description of the transformer architecture consisting of multiple transformer blocks, each with several weight matrices.  - 01:48 Selection of a specific weight matrix to illustrate the LASER process.  - 02:01 Description of singular value decomposition (SVD) used for low-rank approximation and the computational efficiency of the process.  - 02:39 Identification of three choices in performing a LASER intervention: which layer to select, which weight matrix to edit, and the level of approximation.   Benefits of LASER and Its Evaluation  - 03:03 Mention of LASER's ability to reduce the memory footprint of LLMs, enabling broader accessibility.  - 03:24 Evaluation of LASER on the GPT-J LLM using the counterfact question answering dataset to assess model robustness to paraphrases.  - 03:55 Observation that, contrary to expectations, the right LASER intervention can decrease model loss instead of increasing it, indicating an improvement in the pre-trained LLM.  - 04:24 Analysis of the impact of applying LASER to different layers of an LLM, with earlier layers increasing loss and later layers decreasing loss when more approximation is performed.   Generalizability and Analysis of LASER's Effects  - 04:52 Confirmation that LASER's surprising results hold across multiple tasks and different LLMs like Roberta, GPT-J, and LLama2.  - 05:02 Reports of significant performance improvements in certain tasks following LASER intervention.  - 05:20 Brief mention of additional analyses, including gains from rare data points in training data and the removal of semantically correct but erroneous responses by LASER, likening it to a denoising process.   Conclusion  - 05:50 Summary of LASER as an intervention method for LLMs that can increase accuracy while reducing memory usage.  - 06:07 Direction to the paper on arXiv and its upcoming presentation at the iClear conference.  - 06:16 Closing of the talk.Disclaimer: I used gpt4-1106 to summarize the video transcript.  Thismethod may make mistakes in recognizing words

author: @tomn872
processed_text: - Microsoft Research is actively exploring new frontiers in AI, focusing on the transition from emerging technologies to practical applications and how to connect their research with the broader research community. The discussion involves research leaders like AJ, Kamar Ahmed Awadallah, and Sebastian Bubek, who share their aspirations for AI and the challenges they face in achieving them.- The panel highlights the potential of AI to perceive and operate in the real world beyond language, emphasizing the importance of multimodality and the challenges in creating AI systems that can assist in various aspects of life by understanding human goals, intentions, and preferences.- Ahmed Awadallah expresses excitement about advancing towards Artificial General Intelligence (AGI) and the necessity for AI to have capabilities such as memory, history, and a deep understanding of reasoning, which are fundamental for mimicking human thought processes.- The discussion also touches on the limitations of current AI technologies, such as transformers and machine learning models, in replicating human reasoning and intelligence. The importance of high-quality, textbook-like data and the exploration of new methods in model training and reasoning are emphasized as critical areas for research.- The conversation concludes with the importance of transitioning research findings into practical applications rapidly, the role of AI in society and responsible AI development, and the collaboration with the global research community to innovate and build AI responsibly, ensuring safety and reliability in AI applications.

author: @darylallen2485
processed_text: I assume the distinction is in outcomes and performance. Allow me to illustrate. Humans don't need the same quantity of examples to learn patterns. Also, the brain uses much less energy to do what it does than an LLM. Third, the human brain can reason when its exposed to a phenomenon its never seen before. Next token prediction is based on statistics abstracted from a large body of examples. LLMs can't next token predict if the sample size is 1.

author: @therainman7777
processed_text: @@darylallen2485No, that‚Äôs not correct. Modern LLMs are quite capable at reasoning about contexts or scenarios they‚Äôve never seen before. This is called zero-shot learning. They are also capable of learning patterns from a very small number of samples; this is called few-shot learning. GPT-4, for example, does both zero-shot and few-shot learning extremely well. I‚Äôm not sure why you thought they weren‚Äôt capable of this, but you‚Äôre very wrong.Also, while it is true that the average person‚Äôs brain is capable of learning new patterns with relatively few samples, this does not happen in a vacuum; by the time a human‚Äôs brain is capable of doing this that brain has already processed many orders of magnitude more information than modern LLMs are trained on. So in that sense the brain is not actually more efficient as you claim.

author: @gustavnilsson6597
processed_text: @@therainman7777 Yes I can agree with that, however it can still be useful to highlight the limitations.For example, a LLM today does not in fact receive input that it can use to define the degree of which the predictions were successful in real time. This operation is very metabolically expensive so the brain have optimized its behavior to reduce the amounts of this function invocation, but it is critical to reinforcing the predictions of the model. This is where the constraint of the environment, makes the brain more efficient and adaptable.Potentially how it can be solved is to have RAG serve as an actual input that corresponds to what in reasoning is the existing knowledge base, and in vision is light rays. What is missing from there is a reinforcement learning model applied on the predictions with the goal function being derived from the evaluation of the RAG invocation.

author: @0x1EGEN
processed_text: Literally everything breaks if you try hard enough. The point of glass storage is that it's one of the most chemically stable material out there. HDDs are prone to mechanical failure and of course their magnetic discs rot overtime. Same with LTO tapes. CDs are made of plastic and use light-sensitive dye coating which also deteriorates after a few years. There are M-Discs and Gold DVDs which use a metal coat instead of organic coating, making it much more durable and can potentially last for hundreds of years in the right condition, but they cannot store nearly as much data as compared to LTO tapes. Microsoft's glass storage is a replacement of LTO tapes and is intended to be used in an archival library, similar to that of a tape library where everything is sorted via mechanical robot. So you won't ever have to worry about mishandling or dropping the glass.

author: @user-to9ub5xv7o
processed_text: Chapters Summary: 1. Introduction and Panelist Introductions: (0:06 - 0:40)   - Geoff Gordon introduces the panel on the future of reinforcement learning at the Microsoft Research Summit. Panelists are asked to introduce themselves and highlight an important trend in RL research. 2. Emma Brunskill's Insights: (0:40 - 2:30)   - Emma Brunskill, an Associate Professor at Stanford, discusses her work in AI systems, especially in reinforcement learning (RL). She emphasizes the increasing application of RL across various fields and the gap between academic research in RL and its practical applications. 3. Csaba Szepesvari's Perspective: (2:30 - 4:10)   - Csaba Szepesvari from the University of Alberta and DeepMind highlights the potential and challenges in making RL algorithms more robust and scalable. He expresses interest in applications and the need for further research, particularly in areas like partial observability. 4. Sham Kakade's Viewpoint: (4:10 - 5:26)   - Sham Kakade, a professor at the University of Washington and researcher at Microsoft, discusses his work in AI and machine learning, with a focus on RL and natural language processing. He finds the results in program synthesis and mathematical reasoning using planning algorithms to be particularly intriguing. 5. Joelle Pineau's Contributions: (5:26 - 7:31)   - Joelle Pineau from McGill University and Facebook AI Research Labs talks about her journey in RL research, with a focus on healthcare and robotics applications. She emphasizes the importance of reproducibility, scientific integrity, and considering broader criteria like fairness and safety in RL. 6. Craig Boutilier's Remarks: (7:31 - 10:55)   - Craig Boutilier from Google Research discusses his focus on user-centric recommender systems and the critical role of RL in understanding user preferences. He identifies gaps in RL, particularly in dealing with latent state, complex action spaces, and behavioral phenomena. 7. Panel Discussion on Combinatorial Thinking in RL: (10:55 - 32:42)   - Initial discussion on handling combinatorial challenges in RL, focusing on generalization and compositionality in action and state spaces (10:55 - 20:26).   - Further exploration of theoretical aspects, such as the interplay between representations and dynamics, and the impact of RL's interactive nature on learning and generalization (20:26 - 32:42). 8. Exploring Special vs. General-Purpose Architectures in RL: (32:42 - 43:56)   - Introduction of the topic comparing special-purpose architectures versus general-purpose architectures in RL, with specific references to value iteration networks and transformers (32:42 - 33:59).   - Discussion on the efficacy of different architectures in RL, the importance of rigorous experimentation, and the potential limitations and strengths of these architectures (33:59 - 43:56). 9. Closing Remarks: (43:56 - 44:19)   - Geoff Gordon thanks the panelists for their insights and contributions, suggesting the need for a follow-up discussion given the depth of topics covered.

author: @AdrianYang
processed_text: Thank you so much for this lecture. From the point view of digital signal processing, a small downsampling ratio implies large sampling rate which preserves more frequency info (high freq info); a small filter window size (patch size) implies fewer frequency choices of the filter (frequency resolution), which means "smoother" in the corresponding continual domain, and therefore reduces instability. As for translation invariance, fine-grind filters (via more layers) work for not only global but also local translation invariances.Another understanding from me about using small patch size for CNN is, although in signal process field a lager filter window size is preferred, here in CNN the tasks are mainly for classification rather than reconstructing the signal, and therefore stability is more important.

author: @askmiller
processed_text: With the communication thing, the takeaway I got is after the q bits have been entangled and separated, there is no way you can modify the probability of what your qbit will collapse to that doesn't involve also modifying the entangled qbit.  The only way you can modify the other qbit is to send a signal to it so you're stuck still communicating at the speed of light.

author: @askmiller
processed_text: I think what could help with the example is having both black boxes for quantum and classical have the same inputs and outputs, then showing that with just 0 and 1 inputs you cannot solve the problem in 1 query.  I.e. if you choose to send in 0-0, and you get 0-0 you don't know if it's identity or set 0 and if you get 1-0 you don't know if it's bit flip or set 1.  If you send in 0-1 and get 0-1 you don't know if it's set 0 or bit flip and if you get 1-1 you don't know if it's identity or set 1.  If you send in 1-0 and get 1-0 you don't know if it's bit flip or set 1.  If you get 0-0 you don't know if it's set 0 or identity.  And if you send in 1-1 and get 0-1 you don't know if it's set 0 or bit flip and if you get 1-1 you don't know if it's identity or set 1.  The only way to answer that question is if you can send in values other than 0 and 1 down the lines.

processed_text: I will put here something that took me a couple of years to really understand about the whole habit thing and how it can be used in every area of life. And although I understood all the things in the book it just recently clicked for me and everything made sense. Keep with my thought. Probably most of you have had hard time working out, studying or doing something else that you knew it needed to be done, but it was hard and you felt lazy. I know I did. Everybody around us tells us that we need to be disciplined, ambitious, have will power to do things that needed to be done, although we felt inner resilience against them. I know I have talked to myself: " Why do I feel this repulsion against studying, or something else. I need to enforce it, use my willpower, etc." Bullshit! Go again to the brain activity of the rat. It looks lazy, unmotivated, but its brain is working like hell. That's your inner resilience against new things. Your brain doesn't want new things, and when it deals with it, it uses a lot of energy to process the new thing. That's why when you start something new, you can't do much fruitful work, you are quickly exhausted, etc. But when you do just enough regularly, as much as you can every time, without being harsh on yourself, you notice how you can do more and more work, much more effectively, without inner resilience or feeling exhausted. That's the habit stage, the brain no longer is on fire processing new info. In summary, when you start something new, it's absolutely normal to not achieve much, feel quickly exhausted and have inner resilience. The more you do the habit, the more it sticks, until you reach a moment when you can study for several hours in a row, and feel great. That's when you start achieving your goals . Hope you understood my idea.

author: @martm216
processed_text: This question of pattern recognition and memory came up in the Susan Polgar video. Susan seemed to have a phenomenal memory, and she has got an excellent memory, but the gentleman who raised the question had a good point about pattern recognition. They showed Susan for three seconds a fairly full chess position. She instantly replicated this. Then they showed her for three seconds a position with the pieces scattered on random squares. In this case her memory was not a lot better than anyone else's. They said that in the first case she used a memory, or recognition, technique known as 'chunking', whereby certain groups or patterns of pieces, for example the king in a corner behind three pawns with maybe a rook at f8 and a knight at f6, occur typically in a normal chess game. The random position they showed her was never, if ever, likely to occur in any actual game.

author: @martm216
processed_text: One little thing I must question, and this comes up in other videos, is the question of the number of possible games of chess. This is apparently astronomical. A video about Susan Polgar stated that the number of possible games, or maybe it was the number of moves in the number of possible games, was greater than the number of atoms in the known universe. But balance this against the fact that at the top level of human chess the game, under classical time-control of two hours per forty moves, has become very sterile. There is draw after draw and the match is decided on rapid-play shoot-out, like a penalty shoot-out in soccer. Or when one player does manage a win under classical time-control, it is ground out at move a hundred and something from a tiny advantage maintained deep into the endgame, a la Magnus Carlsen. Why? Because the number of POSSIBLE  games is radically different from the number of PROBABLE games, where the openings run along lines of a far more limited number of recognised good sensible moves. author: @KpxUrz5745
processed_text: Can't say I think much of this kind of arbitrage method. There are many far better mathematical ways of augmenting trading. And there are also really robust and timely methods using technical analysis of charts. I know technical analysis sometimes is rejected those who fall for "random walk" studies as some sort of proof that markets must be random. This is utter nonsense. With enough work and patience, the exact point of turnaround in many markets can be identified. Most people crave constant trading action, but superior results can be achieved by not trading at all until the ideal patterns set up. I would never trade any form of arbitrage or "reversion to the mean" methods because those can and will fail very badly.

author: @sabyasachighosh6252
processed_text: I feel that "write the paper" in step 2 is too strong of a constraint. It could be - write down a plan for the project. "Write a paper" forces correctness onto the idea, whereas a plan is free to be incorrect and modified. It's also fundamentally challenging to have claimed to have done the work before even starting the work (papers are typically written in such language). It is much more natural to declare a promise of the work. The main objective behind the "model 2" is that the research should be well-motivated, well-defined, and there should be a concrete plan in place. This is just standard practice for good project management, told in a more confusing term of "write the paper".Step 2 could instead be "write down a plan for your project".

author: @RockyBernstein
processed_text: I find this talk a little more engaging better than those that came after which describe newer Python bytecode.Because of this, I will comment on this talk rather than the others which also have small flaws in them in my opinion.First, a little comment on the work "bytecode". In the context of Python, it is a little ambiguous and vague.Bytecode is a concept that exists outside of Python. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bytecode . In general, it refers to the instruction set of a virtual machine. As correctly mentioned in this talk, it is portable . This was Nicholas Wirth's motivation for introducing it. For high-level bytecode as is found in Python, it is generally compact as well. This is shown implicitly in this and other talks.This compactness was another major factor for its widespread use. Think Turbo Pascal and old IBM PC DOS systems on Intel pre-i386 systems, Intel 8080 and the old Apple Synertek 6502.In the context of Python (and in other bytecode systems), the instructions are organized as a series of amorphous bytes (the "byte" part of "bytecode"), and the first step of a consumer of bytecode like a disassembler or interpreter is to turn these bytes into instructions . Starting with Python 3.6, the disassembler module do a better job at separating these two concepts. Why it took 20 years and something like 30 versions of Python clarify this in the code organization, is to me a bit sad.In 3.6 there was a small push to coin a new word, "wordcode" instead of bytecode since the format switched from one largely one-byte or three-byte instructions to uniformly two-byte instructions. That concept hasn't stuck.Which brings me one small clarification regarding the length of an instruction. While in one sense you can say that "instructions" are one or three bytes before Python 3.6, conceptually, that is not true. When an integer operand value is larger than what can fit in two bytes (pre Python 3.6) or one byte (post Python 3.6). Then one or more "instructions" called EXTENDED_ARG  is used. So several "instructions" are really part of one logical instruction.So I guess in addition to "bytecode" being a little vague, so is "bytecode instruction". In the Python context, "bytecode", as distinct from the general concept of bytecode, refers to the amorphous bytestring instruction part of the overall bytecode encoding system.It is good in this talk to point out the incompleteness or vagueness of "dis" output. As this and other talks point out there are those other fields in the Python's code object that exist. Some of these bits of information is melded into the disassembly output so you can kind of infer what those tables are. For example you can reconstruct the constants pool co_consts   and the various name tables from disassembly output. Other fields like the flags for the code object, or the "filename" that the code object came from one can't infer.However since 2016 (after this talk came out) there is a better disassembler called xdis https://pypi.org/project/xdis/ that shows this information.A tough problem of any talk on "Python bytecode" is that there are something like 40 variants and the drift from the first version to the latest is like the drift in languages between German to Norwegian with Dutch, Danish and Swedish along the way. As a result most projects that use Python's  dis  module tend to suffer the problem that they need a little to a lot of tweaking for the next version of Python. And that they work only for the version of Python interpreter running the tool.The tool mentioned here, Maynard, apparently suffers this problem - there were only two versions ever released. Byterun which uses xdis has the same problem. So again , xdis can assist here a little bit, although tweaking from version to version is still necessary.I could write a bit more about little small corrections that would have made this talk just a tad better. Small example: using the word "Computation Operations" rather than "Arithmetic Operations" because one does not think of string and possibly boolean operations ("contains", or "is in") as "Arithmetic". However let me leave it that if this talk is given again or if anyone in the future has a talk on bytecode, if you run the talk by me I'd be happy to make suggestions or corrections.
